Treat a malformed number in an NLM .def file as a fatal error, not a warning.

Stock nlmconv prints 'bad number' for e.g. 'STACK bladiebla' but still exits 0
and silently writes strtol()'s fallback value 0 into the header field (stack
size, version, etc.), which is far more dangerous than failing the build.
nlmheader.c is bison output shipped in the release tarball; it is patched
identically so the fix applies without regenerating it (no bison needed).

--- binutils-2.30.orig/binutils/nlmheader.y	2026-07-19 12:27:38.118678752 +0000
+++ binutils-2.30/binutils/nlmheader.y	2026-07-19 12:27:38.119755761 +0000
@@ -858,7 +858,7 @@
 
   ret = strtol (s, &send, 10);
   if (*send != '\0')
-    nlmheader_warn (_("bad number"), -1);
+    nlmheader_error (_("bad number"));
   return ret;
 }
 
--- binutils-2.30.orig/binutils/nlmheader.c	2026-07-19 12:27:38.120925687 +0000
+++ binutils-2.30/binutils/nlmheader.c	2026-07-19 12:27:38.121953577 +0000
@@ -2537,7 +2537,7 @@
 
   ret = strtol (s, &send, 10);
   if (*send != '\0')
-    nlmheader_warn (_("bad number"), -1);
+    nlmheader_error (_("bad number"));
   return ret;
 }
 
